---
import Breadcrumbs from '@/components/Breadcrumbs.astro'
import Container from '@/components/Container.astro'
import Link from '@/components/Link.astro'
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro'
---

<Layout>
  <Container class="flex grow flex-col gap-y-6">
    <Breadcrumbs
      items={[
        { label: 'Projects', href: '/projects', icon: 'lucide:archive' },
        {
          label: 'Tethra',
          href: '/projects/tethra',
          icon: 'lucide:sticky-note',
        },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="flex flex-col rounded-none pt-10 font-sans" role="main">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-between gap-5 max-md:max-w-full">
        <div class="flex flex-col max-md:max-w-full">
          <svg width="140" height="32" viewBox="0 0 140 32" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="self-start text-black dark:text-white">
            <path d="M19.2002 3.2002L22.4004 6.40039H25.5996V9.59961L28.7998 12.7998H32V19.2002H28.7998L25.5996 22.4004V25.5996H22.4004L19.2002 28.7998V32H12.7998V28.7998L9.59961 25.5996H6.40039V22.209L3.3916 19.2002H0V12.7998H3.2002L6.40039 9.59961V6.40039H9.59961L12.7998 3.2002V0H19.2002V3.2002Z" fill="currentColor"/>
            <path d="M61.2705 27.5H52.6309V26.0674H55.5137V5.90527H49.748V7.34668H48.3066V8.78809H46.874V10.2207H45.4414V7.34668H46.874V3.02246H48.3066V4.46387H67.0273V3.02246H68.4688V7.34668H67.0273V10.2207H65.5859V5.90527H58.3877V26.0674H61.2705V27.5ZM76.3613 27.5H69.1631V26.0674H67.7217V24.626H66.2803V21.7432H64.8477V17.4277H66.2803V14.5449H67.7217V15.9863H76.3613V14.5449H74.9199V13.1035H69.1631V11.6621H76.3613V13.1035H77.8027V14.5449H79.2441V17.4277H67.7217V21.7432H69.1631V24.626H70.6045V26.0674H76.3613V27.5ZM69.1631 14.5449H67.7217V13.1035H69.1631V14.5449ZM79.2441 24.626H77.8027V23.1846H79.2441V24.626ZM77.8027 26.0674H76.3613V24.626H77.8027V26.0674ZM88.6045 27.5H84.2803V26.0674H82.8389V13.1035H81.4062V11.6621H82.8389V10.2207H84.2803V8.78809H85.7217V11.6621H90.0459V13.1035H85.7217V26.0674H88.6045V27.5ZM90.0459 26.0674H88.6045V24.626H90.0459V26.0674ZM97.9561 27.5H92.1992V26.0674H93.6318V4.46387H92.1992V3.02246H93.6318V1.58105H95.0732V0.148438H96.5146V13.1035H97.9561V14.5449H96.5146V26.0674H97.9561V27.5ZM108.758 27.5H102.992V26.0674H104.434V14.5449H102.992V13.1035H97.9561V11.6621H104.434V13.1035H105.875V14.5449H107.316V26.0674H108.758V27.5ZM116.694 27.5H110.938V26.0674H112.37V14.5449H110.938V13.1035H112.37V11.6621H113.812V10.2207H115.253V13.1035H116.694V14.5449H115.253V26.0674H116.694V27.5ZM122.451 14.5449H119.577V13.1035H116.694V11.6621H122.451V14.5449ZM139.01 27.5H136.127V26.0674H133.253V24.626H134.686V18.8604H133.253V17.4277H134.686V14.5449H133.253V13.1035H128.929V14.5449H127.487V15.9863H124.613V14.5449H126.046V13.1035H127.487V11.6621H134.686V13.1035H136.127V14.5449H137.568V26.0674H139.01V27.5ZM133.253 20.3018H128.929V18.8604H133.253V20.3018ZM133.253 27.5H127.487V26.0674H126.046V24.626H124.613V21.7432H126.046V20.3018H128.929V21.7432H127.487V24.626H128.929V26.0674H133.253V27.5Z" fill="currentColor"/>
          </svg>
          <div
            class="mt-5 text-lg font-medium leading-tight tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
          >
            A desktop AI chat app that keeps your conversations local and lets
            you share them on the web.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div
          class="flex w-full items-center justify-between gap-2 self-start text-right text-sm leading-loose tracking-tighter text-accent md:w-auto md:flex-col"
        >
          <div>Product, Full-Stack Dev</div>
          <div class="self-end">2025</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8 flex items-center justify-center rounded-xl bg-gradient-to-br from-violet-50 to-indigo-100 dark:from-zinc-900 dark:to-zinc-800">
        <div
          class="my-auto flex w-[1683px] max-w-[1683px] flex-col self-stretch overflow-hidden rounded-xl max-md:max-w-full"
        >
          <img
            loading="lazy"
            src="/static/images/tethra-showcase.png"
            alt="Tethra AI chat application showcase"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover max-md:max-w-full"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="mt-11 flex w-full items-center justify-between gap-10 max-md:mt-10 max-md:max-w-full max-md:flex-wrap"
      >
        <div
          class="my-auto flex w-[925px] min-w-[240px] flex-col self-stretch pt-2 text-sm leading-loose tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
        >
          <div
            class="mr-20 text-2xl leading-8 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:mr-2.5 max-md:max-w-full"
          >
            A cross-platform desktop AI chat application built with Tauri and
            React 19 — conversations stay on your machine, but you can share
            any of them as a public web link whenever you want.
          </div>
          <div class="mr-16 mt-7 leading-5 max-md:mr-2.5 max-md:max-w-full">
            Tethra started from a frustration I had: I was constantly
            switching tabs between ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini depending on
            what I needed. Everything was siloed. No shared history, no way
            to compare responses, no way to share a conversation without
            screenshotting it.
            <br />
            <br />
            So I built Tethra — a single native app that talks to all of them. Your
            conversations live in a local SQLite database. You can switch models
            mid-conversation. And if you ever want to share something, the app
            generates a public URL that anyone can open in a browser, no account needed.
          </div>
          <ul
            class="mt-6 list-none space-y-3 pl-4 max-md:max-w-full max-md:pl-4"
          >
            <li class="flex gap-2">
              <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
              Built a cross-platform desktop app using Tauri and React 19 with
              TypeScript — native performance without shipping a full Chromium bundle
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-2">
              <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
              Integrated OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and DeepSeek via the Vercel AI
              SDK for a consistent streaming interface across all providers
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-2">
              <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
              Designed a web sharing system that publishes conversations as
              read-only public URLs without requiring any authentication
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-2">
              <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
              Used TanStack Router for file-based routing and Motion for smooth
              UI transitions throughout the app
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div
          class="my-auto flex w-[408px] min-w-[240px] flex-col items-start self-stretch py-0.5 pr-14 text-sm font-semibold leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground"
        >
          <h2 class="leading-none">Contribution</h2>
          <div class="mt-3 text-sm tracking-tighter text-foreground">
            UI/UX Design, React/TypeScript Frontend,
            <br />
            Rust/Tauri Backend, AI Provider Integration
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 text-sm tracking-tighter text-foreground">
            SQLite Schema, Web Sharing System
          </div>
          <h2 class="mt-10 leading-none">Repository</h2>
          <a
            href="https://github.com/decentparadox/tethra"
            class="mt-2.5 whitespace-nowrap text-base leading-none tracking-tighter text-accent hover:underline focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-violet-400"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            github.com/decentparadox/tethra
          </a>
          <h2 class="mt-10 leading-none">Stack</h2>
          <div class="mt-3 text-sm tracking-tighter text-foreground">
            React 19, TypeScript, Tauri, Rust
            <br />
            SQLite, Vercel AI SDK, TanStack Router
            <br />
            Shadcn/ui, Tailwind CSS, Motion
          </div>
          <h2 class="mt-16 leading-none max-md:mt-10">Duration</h2>
          <div class="z-10 mt-3.5 w-60 text-sm tracking-tighter text-foreground">
            Design & Architecture: 2 weeks
            <br />
            Core Development: 8 weeks
            <br />
            AI Integration & Sharing: 5 weeks
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="flex flex-col rounded-none font-sans">
      <div class="w-full max-md:max-w-full">
        <div class="flex gap-5 max-md:flex-col">
          <div class="flex w-6/12 flex-col gap-5 max-md:w-full">
            <div
              class="flex h-[567px] w-full shrink-0 rounded-xl bg-foreground dark:bg-zinc-900 overflow-hidden"
              role="img"
              aria-label="Tethra application interface showcase"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              <div class="my-auto p-4">
                <div class="flex gap-5 flex-col">
                  <div class="flex w-[60%] flex-col max-md:ml-0 max-md:w-full">
                    <div
                      class="my-auto mr-0 flex flex-col self-stretch text-2xl font-semibold leading-8 tracking-tighter text-background max-md:mt-10"
                    >
                      <img
                        loading="lazy"
                        src="/static/images/tethra-logo.svg"
                        alt="Tethra Logo"
                        class="aspect-square w-[46px] rounded-none object-contain"
                      />
                      <div
                        class="mt-12 max-md:mt-10 dark:text-white"
                        role="contentinfo"
                        tabindex="0"
                      >
                        One interface for all your AI conversations — local
                        first, shareable when you want
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="flex flex-col ml-0 w-full">
                    <img
                      loading="lazy"
                      src="/static/images/tethra-mobile-mockup.png"
                      alt="Tethra Interface Mockup"
                      class="aspect-[1.53] w-full grow object-contain max-md:max-w-full"
                    />
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <img
              loading="lazy"
              src="/static/images/tethra/home.png"
              alt="Tethra application home screen"
              class="w-full rounded-xl object-contain"
            />
          </div>
          <div class="flex w-6/12 flex-col gap-5 max-md:w-full">
            <div
              class="flex w-full grow flex-col items-start rounded-xl bg-foreground py-7 pl-6 pr-20 text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tighter text-background max-md:mt-6 max-md:max-w-full max-md:px-5"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              <div class="leading-8 max-md:max-w-full">
                Every AI provider has its own interface. The real cost is
                context — you lose it every time you switch tabs.
              </div>
              <div
                class="mt-60 font-serif text-6xl leading-none tracking-tighter text-accent max-md:mt-10 max-md:text-4xl"
                aria-label="Four AI providers in one app"
              >
                4+
              </div>
              <div class="mt-8 leading-none max-md:max-w-full">
                AI providers unified in a single local interface.
              </div>
            </div>
            <img
              loading="lazy"
              src="/static/images/tethra/settings.png"
              alt="Tethra application settings screen"
              class="w-full rounded-xl object-contain"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-16 flex w-[842px] max-w-full flex-col pb-12 max-md:mt-10">
        <div
          class="text-2xl font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
          tabindex="0"
        >
          The problem with how we use AI today:
        </div>
        <div
          class="mt-6 text-sm leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
          tabindex="0"
        >
          I was doing a lot of AI-assisted work across research, coding, and writing.
          Every provider has something different to offer — GPT-4o is solid for
          coding, Claude is great for writing, Gemini handles long contexts well.
          But switching between them means losing history, losing context, and
          constantly re-explaining where you left off. Web interfaces also mean
          your conversations are stored on someone else's server by default,
          which I wasn't thrilled about.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-10 max-md:max-w-full">
        <div class="flex gap-1">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex min-h-[72px] flex-1 flex-col pl-7 max-md:max-w-full">
            <div
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              Fragmented Context
            </div>
            <div
              class="mt-3 text-sm leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              Every AI provider is its own silo. Conversations don't travel
              between apps, so you end up either sticking to one model or
              losing context every time you switch. Neither is great.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-1">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex min-h-[72px] flex-1 flex-col pl-7 max-md:max-w-full">
            <div
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              No Ownership Over Your Data
            </div>
            <div
              class="mt-3 text-sm leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              With web-based interfaces, all your conversations live on external
              servers. There's no local copy, no offline access, and no guarantee
              about how long they'll be retained or what they're used for.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-1">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex min-h-[72px] max-w-full flex-col pl-7">
            <div
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              Sharing is Clunky
            </div>
            <div
              class="mt-3 text-sm leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
              tabindex="0"
            >
              Sharing a useful conversation usually means screenshotting it or
              copying the text. ChatGPT added share links but you're still
              locked into one provider. There was no clean way to share from
              a local-first app.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        class="text-sm mt-6 flex flex-col gap-4 leading-5 tracking-tighter text-foreground max-md:max-w-full"
        tabindex="0"
      >
        <p>
          I picked Tauri over Electron because I didn't want to ship a 200MB
          app. Tauri uses the system's native webview and a Rust backend, which
          brings the binary down to something reasonable. The tradeoff is that
          you're writing some Rust, which has a steeper learning curve, but
          for the core functionality — file system access, SQLite, IPC — it
          wasn't too bad.
        </p>
        <p>
          React 19 with TypeScript handles the entire frontend. I used TanStack
          Router for file-based routing because it felt more natural than
          React Router for this kind of app, and the type safety on params and
          search is genuinely good. Shadcn/ui gave me a set of accessible
          components to build from rather than starting completely from scratch.
        </p>

        <div
          class="text-2xl font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
          tabindex="0"
        >
          Getting multiple providers to work consistently
        </div>
        <p>
          Every AI provider has a slightly different API. Some stream differently,
          some have different auth schemes, some support function calling differently.
          The Vercel AI SDK was a lifesaver here — it abstracts away a lot of
          that inconsistency and gives you a unified streaming interface. I was
          initially skeptical about adding another dependency for this, but it
          genuinely saved a lot of time and the library is well maintained.
        </p>
        <p>
          Conversations are stored in SQLite via Tauri's SQL plugin. Each conversation
          has an ID, the messages stored as JSON, metadata like model and provider,
          and a flag for whether it's been published to the web. This local-first
          approach means everything works offline and the user owns their data
          completely. I didn't want to run any kind of sync service, so the
          simplicity of just writing to a local file felt right.
        </p>

        <div
          class="text-2xl font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
          tabindex="0"
        >
          The web sharing part
        </div>
        <p>
          This was the most interesting problem to solve. Local conversations
          are great, but sometimes you want to send someone a link to a useful
          exchange you had with an AI. The approach I went with: when you
          choose to share a conversation, it gets uploaded to a lightweight
          backend that serves it as a static read-only page. The conversation
          stays in your local SQLite database — the shared version is just
          a snapshot that can be revoked.
        </p>
        <p>
          The public share page is intentionally simple — just the conversation
          rendered cleanly with markdown support. No login required to view it,
          and the URL is opaque enough that it won't be guessed. Not a perfect
          privacy model, but for casual sharing it works well and doesn't require
          the recipient to have an account anywhere.
        </p>
      </div>

      <img
        loading="lazy"
        src="/static/images/tethra/banner.png"
        alt="Tethra banner"
        class="mt-8 w-full rounded-xl object-cover max-md:hidden"
      />
      <img
        loading="lazy"
        src="/static/images/tethra/banner-mobile.png"
        alt="Tethra banner"
        class="mt-8 w-full rounded-xl object-cover md:hidden"
      />
      <section
        class="flex max-w-[842px] mt-8 flex-col text-sm tracking-tighter"
        aria-labelledby="reflection-title"
      >
        <h2
          id="reflection-title"
          class="text-2xl font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
        >
          Reflection:
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-6 leading-5 text-foreground max-md:max-w-full">
          Tethra pushed me into parts of the stack I hadn't worked with much
          before — Rust, SQLite at the application level, and the details of
          how streaming AI APIs actually work under the hood. It also made me
          think a lot about data ownership and what "local-first" actually
          means in practice when you're building for normal users.
        </p>
        <article class="mt-6 flex w-full gap-2">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex w-full flex-col items-start py-1 px-2 max-md:max-w-full max-md:pl-5">
            <h3
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
            >
              Tauri is worth the Rust tax:
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-4 leading-5 text-foreground max-md:max-w-full">
              The smaller binary size and memory footprint compared to Electron
              are real. Writing some Rust for the backend commands took time
              to get comfortable with, but the IPC model is clean and the
              compiler catches a lot of issues before they become runtime bugs.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 leading-loose text-accent max-md:max-w-full">
              I'd reach for Tauri again for any desktop project where
              performance and binary size matter.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="mt-6 flex w-full gap-2">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex w-full flex-col items-start py-1 px-2 max-md:max-w-full max-md:pl-5">
            <h3
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
            >
              Abstraction layers save real time:
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-4 leading-5 text-foreground max-md:max-w-full">
              Using the Vercel AI SDK instead of integrating each provider
              directly meant I wasn't reinventing the wheel for every API
              difference. The tradeoff is less control over edge cases, but
              for most use cases the abstraction is the right call.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 leading-loose text-accent max-md:mt-10 max-md:max-w-full">
              Good abstractions exist for a reason — use them.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="mt-6 flex w-full gap-2">
          <div class="w-1 bg-accent"></div>
          <div class="flex w-full flex-col items-start py-1 px-2 max-md:max-w-full max-md:pl-5">
            <h3
              class="text-sm font-semibold leading-none tracking-tighter text-foreground"
            >
              Local-first is a design commitment, not just a technical one:
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-4 leading-5 text-foreground max-md:max-w-full">
              Once you commit to local-first, every feature decision flows
              from that. The web sharing feature needed careful thought about
              what it means to "publish" something from a local database —
              the snapshot model turned out to be the right answer.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 leading-loose text-accent max-md:mt-10 max-md:max-w-full">
              The architecture of your app shapes what you can and can't
              build later — choose it deliberately.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </section>
    </div>

  </Container>
</Layout>
